'I reached to the top of the cooler and retrieved my .22-caliber,' Ferrell said, according to The Tennessean. 'And I fired it. I fired in fear.'

Ferrell said he grabbed bar towels to try and stop the bleeding, but then began to panic and put an unloaded gun next to Mills.

'Why would that cause you to panic?' David Raybin, Ferrell's attorney, asked him.

'Because I thought I'd, because I thought I'd done something wrong at that point,' Ferrell said about the shooting, which happened at about 5am.

